<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-649-584  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 649 584.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  July 16 1990 v7 n28 p117(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>PC Makers re-evaluate policies for ecology's sake. (Valley Voices)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bajarin, Tim.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Companies such as HP, Apple and IBM that have been abusing theenvironment for decades have begun to take a leadership role indeveloping ecology-conscious policies.andP;  The impetus to establishenvironmental policies comes from the very top at HP.andP;  DavidPackard's daughter is executive director of the Monterey BayAquarium and an environmentalist and has influenced her father'sawareness of environmental issues.andP;  A task force designated tooversee and develop company actions on environmental issues hasbeen established by HP's board.andP;  The company is implementing anextensive program to eliminate the use of chemicalchlorofluorocarbons (CFC) which depletes the earth's ozone layer.andO;HP's Avondale, FL, site reduced its CFC use by 80 percent duringthe first six months of 1990.andP;  Recycling paper and packagingmaterials are also a key part of HP's environmental efforts.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Hewlett-Packard Co. (environmental policy).andO;Ticker:    HWP.andO;Topic:     EcologyRecyclingEnvironmental ProtectionComputer industry.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Last April marked the 20th anniversary of Earth Day, an event that focusesthe world's attention on environmental concerns.andP;  Those issues are far moreserious today than they were 20 years ago.andP;  &quot;If the planet as we know it isto be saved,&quot; said Dennis Hayes, organizer of the event, &quot;we must begin totake responsibility.&quot;andM;After decades of unchecked abuse, there are signs that people in high placesare beginning to do just that.andP;  Companies like Hewlett-Packard, IBM andApple, which have contributed to the problem, are now addressing it by takinga leadership role in developing policies that will make them environmentallyresponsible.andM;HP's concern comes from the top.andP;  David Packard's daughter, Julie Packard, isthe executive director of the Monterey Bay Aquarium.andP;  She's a leadingenvironmentalist and a major influence on her father's awareness of theproblems facing the planet.andM;HP's board has established a task force charged with overseeing anddeveloping company positions and actions on environmental issues.andP;  The teamis already having an impact.andM;The company's Boise, Idaho, site now designs and manufactures forenvironmental risk reduction, and the San Diego division created a chemicalreview council to provide guidance and expertise on chemical-relatedproduct-development issues.andM;One of the greatest environmental hazards facing us today is the depletion ofthe earth's ozone, which scientists have linked to the use of the chemicalchlorofluorocarbon (CFC).andM;CFC, which has also been tied to the greenhouse effect, is widely used in theelectronics industry as a cleansing agent.andP;  High-technology applicationstoday represent about 12 percent of worldwide CFC use.andP;  In 1989, acompanywide survey discovered that HP's worldwide manufacturing alone usessome 1.3 million pounds of CFC annually.andM;The company has embarked on a comprehensive program to reduce and eventuallyeliminate CFC use.andP;  Its timetable is based on a schedule for CFCmanufacturers established by the 1987 Montreal Protocol on Substances thatdeplete the ozone.andP;  Signed by 45 countries and now law in the United States,it requires a 50 percent reduction in CFC production by the year 2000.andM;HP management hopes to achieve that goal internally by 1995, and is alreadyseeing some impressive results.andP;  HP's Microwave Technology Division andNetwork Measurements Division cut CFC use by 25 percent last year by usingsubstances that have less of an impact on the ozone and, where possible, byshifting to water-based cleansing agents.andM;The Avondale, Pa., site cut CFC use by 80 percent in the last six months byreplacing CFC-based sprays with carbon-dioxide-propelled cans of alcoholsolvent and by changing degreasing hardware and processes.andP;  And the Boiselocation -- the largest CFC user in Idaho -- has set a goal of eliminatingCFC use completely in four years.andM;Recycling is central to HP's environmental efforts.andP;  All company packagingmaterials are 100 percent recyclable.andP;  And while many foam materials do notyet have recyclable alternatives, HP is working to reduce the amount of thesematerials used for shipping.andM;All HP sites have paper recycling centers.andP;  Last year, offices in the LosAngeles area alone recycled 25 tons of of paper.andP;  The Fort Collins, Colo.,andO;site recycles used furniture and office supplies, including three-ringbinders, by donating them to the local school district.andM;Apple and IBM have also taken drastic steps to make themselves moreenvironmentally responsible.andP;  In my next column, I'll look at their efforts.andM;----------Tim Bajarin is a partner at Creative Strategies Research International, amarket-research and consulting firm based in Santa Clara, Calif.andO;</TEXT></DOC>